article.description: Jermaine O'Neal scored 32 points and grabbed 10 rebounds and Brad Miller had 25 points as the Indiana Pacers beat the Phoenix Suns 97-87 Friday night.
article.headline: O'Neal dominates inside, Pacers stay in race
article.linkText: Pacers get badly needed victory over Suns
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Jermaine O'Neal carried Indiana in the fourth quarter. Now he's hoping to get the Pacers into the playoffs. O'Neal scored 32 points and grabbed 10 rebounds, and Brad Miller had 25 points as Indiana beat the Phoenix Suns 97-87 Friday night. The Pacers desperately needed the victory after dropping five of their last six to fall into a tie with Toronto for the eighth and final playoff spot in the East. The Raptors are 2-0 this season against Indiana with head-to-head games remaining Sunday and Wednesday. The Raptors defeated Chicago 98-96 Friday to keep pace with Indiana. "This is huge, getting this win, especially going into Sunday's game in Toronto," O'Neal said. "Getting this win and going up there and getting a win would be huge." The Pacers relied heavily on O'Neal in the fourth. He was one of four Pacers who played all 12 minutes in the quarter. "This is the team that I want so see us have the rest of the year," O'Neal said. "Everybody is helping and when everybody helps, we win." But the win wasn't easy. The Pacers, who blew an 11-point lead in the fourth quarter against Boston on Tuesday, nearly squandered a 22-point lead late in the third. Jake Tsakalidis, Joe Johnson and John Wallace combined for 17 points in the final 5:35 of the third, pulling Phoenix to 79-67. Tsakalidis, who led Phoenix with 20 points and 12 rebounds, hit a jumper to start the fourth to make it 79-69, capping a 16-4 run. Indiana's Reggie Miller grabbed the long rebound off his own miss and hit a baseline 3-pointer to push the lead back to 15 with 8:06 remaining. But a basket by Wallace, who had 12 points, and consecutive baskets by Tsakalidis sliced the gap to 90-81 with 3:47 remaining. The Suns kept it close, getting two straight baskets by Wallace and Johnson to make it 94-87 with 1:20 left, but that was as close as they would get. Twice early in the fourth when the Suns closed within nine, O'Neal responded with baskets to restore the double-digit lead. He scored 10 points in the fourth. "I've got to be the guy the team wants me to be, and that's controlling both ends of the floor," O'Neal said. Coach Isiah Thomas played O'Neal, Reggie Miller, Jonathan Bender and Kevin Ollie the entire fourth quarter. "I just thought that group out there had a good flow going," Thomas said. "They had good rhythm. I didn't want to change that." Johnson finished with 17 points and Stephon Marbury had 12 for Phoenix, which has lost three straight. The Pacers scored 26 points off 18 Phoenix turnovers. "We were making the defensive stops I thought we had to make, but we just made too many mistakes," Suns coach Frank Johnson said. Bender had 14 points, Reggie Miller added 11 and Brad Miller had nine rebounds. O'Neal went 14-for-26 from the field and Brad Miller made 10 of 19 shots, matching his best point total with Indiana. The Pacers shot 57 percent in the second quarter, ending it with a 16-6 run that built a 57-42 halftime lead. Indiana took a 75-63 lead in the third following Jamaal Tinsley's 3-pointer. Tinsley, at the top of the key, attempted an alley-oop pass to O'Neal under the basket, but the ball went in for the basket.

Game notes
Phoenix assistant Al Bianchi was whistled for a technical in the first quarter. Brad Miller was called for one in the third. Miller also was called for a flagrant foul, his fifth this season. Replays clearly showed Miller trying to block Tsakalidis' shot. ... Phoenix's Alton Ford also was called for a technical. ... Phoenix's Shawn Marion caught an elbow in the face from Bender and sat out the final 11:10. He sat on the bench with an ice pack under his right eye. He had seven points. ... O'Neal's season high was 38 on Dec. 22 against Cleveland. ... With two blocked shots, O'Neal surpassed Steve Stipanovich for eighth place on Indiana's career list. ...Indiana's Ron Mercer missed his fourth straight game with back spasms. ...The Pacers finished 15-13 against the Western Conference. ...The Suns were 5-for-9 from the free throw line.
